    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial document chunks, here are the accounting policies governing satellite manufacturing, orbital AI compute costs, capitalization vs. expensing, inventory, and property, plant, and equipment (PP&E):\n\n### 1. Satellite Manufacturing and Orbital AI Compute Satellite Costs\n*   **Capitalized Components:** Satellites are categorized as PP&E. The capitalized costs include all expenses to build the satellites—specifically parts, labor, and allocated overhead—as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to launch the satellites into orbit. These launch costs include an allocation of the flight vehicle costs.\n*   **Useful Life Estimation:** The useful lives of satellite assets are estimated based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer technology. \n*   **Depreciation:** Broadband satellites are depreciated over a 5-year useful life, while first-generation mobile satellites are depreciated over a 3-year useful life.\n*   **Orbital AI Compute Satellites:** While specific accounting policies for orbital AI compute satellites mirror standard satellite policies (capitalizing manufacturing and launch costs), the company notes that in-orbit construction costs are essentially replaced by launch costs and satellite production costs. The company expects its advanced satellite manufacturing capabilities to allow it to build AI compute satellites at scale and lower cost than terrestrial data center construction.\n\n### 2. Capitalization vs. Expensing of Manufacturing and Maintenance Costs\n*   **Expensed Costs:** Expenditures for routine maintenance and repairs that do not extend the lives of the respective assets are expensed as incurred.\n*   **Capitalized Costs:** Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements that increase the functionality, output, or expected life of an asset are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the asset\'s identified useful life.\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** For all segments, Cost of Revenue includes the cost of materials, depreciation and amortization, shipping, payment processor fees, infrastructure costs (rocket, kit, and satellite manufacturing facilities, and data center costs), allocated overhead, and employee compensation. \n\n### 3. Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E) Capitalization & AI Infrastructure\n*   **Construction in Progress (CIP):** CIP primarily consists of ongoing construction and expansion of facilities and equipment, as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service.\n*   **Capitalized Interest:** The company capitalizes interest costs associated with the significant acquisition or construction of PP&E. \n    *   **Initiation:** Capitalization begins once activities necessary to get the asset ready for its intended use commence.\n    *   **Calculation:** It is calculated using the average amount of accumulated expenditures during the preparation period and a capitalization rate derived from the company’s weighted average borrowing rate (if there are no specific borrowings for the project).\n    *   **Cessation:** Capitalization ceases on any portions that are substantially completed and ready for their intended use. The capitalized interest becomes part of the asset\'s historical cost and is depreciated over its estimated useful life.\n    *   **AI Infrastructure Application:** Interest is capitalized during construction for significant long-term projects, such as AI infrastructure data centers and launch facilities. For the three months ended March 31, 2026, $7 million in interest was capitalized; for the year ended December 31, 2025, $169 million was capitalized.\n*   **Share-Based Compensation:** Share-based compensation is also capitalized into PP&E, net.\n\n### 4. Inventory Capitalization\nThe provided text does not explicitly detail a standalone "inventory capitalization" policy for raw materials or work-in-process. However, it implicitly addresses the capitalization of manufacturing costs by stating that direct parts, labor, and allocated overhead are capitalized directly into the finished satellite assets (PP&E) rather than being held as inventory. \n\n### 5. Impairment Evaluation\n*   **Policy:** The company evaluates impairment of its PP&E assets at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities.\n*   **Recent Charges:** \n    *   **Space Segment:** Recorded $24 million (Q1 2025) and $38 million (FY 2025) in impairment charges related to the write-off of damaged flight vehicles.\n    *   **Connectivity Segment:** Recorded impairment charges (part of the $38 million in FY 2025 and $63 million in FY 2024) related to an abandoned production line and damaged satellite hardware.\n    *   **AI Segment:** Recorded $36 million (FY 2024) and $54 million (FY 2023) in impairment charges related to leasehold improvements and office equipment as part of facilities consolidation efforts, which were reflected in Restructuring charges. There were no PP&E impairment charges in Q1 2026.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
