    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Orbital AI Compute Satellites: Useful Life, Depreciation, and Capitalization\n\n## Specific Useful Life for Orbital AI Compute Satellites\n\nThe text **does not specify a distinct useful life for orbital AI compute satellites**, because they have not yet been deployed — deployment is expected "as early as 2028." The general satellite category in the PP&E useful life table shows:\n\n| Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| Satellites | **3 – 5 years** |\n\nMore specifically, the Company states:\n- **Broadband satellites:** five-year useful life\n- **First-generation mobile satellites:** three-year useful life\n\nUseful lives for all satellite assets are estimated based on **engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer satellite technology.**\n\n## Depreciation Period and Method\n\nSatellites are depreciated using the **straight-line method** over their estimated useful lives (3–5 years). The text does not assign a separate depreciation period to orbital AI compute satellites, implying they would fall under the existing satellite classification once placed in service.\n\nA critical sensitivity disclosure reinforces the materiality of these estimates:\n\n> "If the average useful life of our satellite assets had been changed by one year, it would have an approximately **$480 million** and **$170 million** impact on our operating income for the year ended December 31, 2025 and three months ended March 31, 2026, respectively."\n\n## Capitalization of Manufacturing Costs\n\nSatellite costs **are capitalized as PP&E**. The policy states:\n\n> "Satellites include costs to build the satellites (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as **capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to launch the satellites to orbit, which include an allocation of the flight vehicle [costs]."\n\nAdditionally, **AI infrastructure not yet placed in service** is captured under **Construction in Progress**:\n\n> "Construction in progress is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as **AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service**."\n\nInterest is also capitalized during construction for significant long-term projects, including AI infrastructure data centers.\n\n## Early Retirement Risk Specific to Orbital AI Compute\n\nThe text explicitly warns that orbital AI compute satellites may be retired **sooner** than estimated useful lives:\n\n> "These retirements may occur sooner than our estimates for the useful lives of our satellites... Space based compute also introduces orbital debris risk."\n\nThe Risk Factors section adds that once deployed, orbital AI compute infrastructure **"will not be readily accessible, and as a result, will not be easily repaired or upgraded, such that any component failures could result in permanent capacity loss, accelerated depreciation, decommissioning or need for replacement."**\n\n## Summary\n\n| Item | Treatment |\n|---|---|\n| **Useful life (orbital AI compute satellites)** | Not separately stated; falls under general satellite category of **3–5 years** |\n| **Depreciation method** | Straight-line over estimated useful life |\n| **Manufacturing costs** | **Capitalized as PP&E** (parts, labor, overhead, plus launch costs) |\n| **Pre-deployment costs** | Included in **Construction in Progress** until placed in service |\n| **Capitalized interest** | Yes, during construction period for significant AI infrastructure projects |\n| **Early retirement risk** | Explicitly disclosed; could trigger **accelerated depreciation** or impairment |',
