    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# AI Segment Cost Classification\n\n## AI Segment Cost of Revenue (COGS)\n\nBased on the disclosures, the AI segment\'s cost of revenue includes the following components:\n\n1. **Infrastructure costs**, which consist primarily of:\n   - Data center facility costs (lease and hosting costs)\n   - Related support, maintenance, energy, and bandwidth costs\n   - Depreciation of servers and networking equipment\n   - Public cloud hosting costs\n   - Employee compensation costs (salaries, benefits, and share-based compensation)\n\n2. **Revenue share expenses**\n3. **Payment processor fees**\n4. **Payments to creators**\n5. **Amortization of acquired intangible assets**\n6. **Allocated labor and overhead costs**\n\nThe company expects AI cost of revenue to increase in absolute dollars as revenue grows, but decrease as a percentage of revenue as products are monetized and service offerings expand.\n\n## AI Segment R&D Expenses\n\nAI segment R&D expenses relate to:\n\n- Training of Grok (frontier model)\n- Development, build, and testing of next-generation AI-enabled products\n- Data center costs to train AI-enabled products\n\nThese costs include:\n- Cloud computing expenses\n- Employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation)\n- Power generation costs\n- Depreciation of data center assets, including processors\n- Equipment lease expenses\n- Networking equipment\n\nThe company expects AI R&D expenses to increase both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue as it invests in compute infrastructure for Grok, with potential additional increases from the compute agreement with Cursor.\n\n## AI Segment SG&A Expenses\n\nAI SG&A consists primarily of employee compensation for sales, marketing, finance, legal, IT, HR, and administrative employees, plus professional services fees (consulting, content moderation, legal, accounting), facilities costs, and supporting overhead.\n\n## Satellite Manufacturing Costs and the AI Segment\n\n### Classification of AI Compute Satellites\n\nThe disclosures indicate that **AI compute satellites are treated as capital expenditures (property, plant, and equipment)** rather than being expensed immediately through COGS or R&D. Key evidence:\n\n1. **Capitalized as construction in progress**: The property, plant, and equipment note states that "Construction in progress is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service."\n\n2. **Capital expenditure reporting**: The AI segment reported capital expenditures of $12,727 million in 2025 and $7,723 million in Q1 2026, reflecting massive investment in compute infrastructure including data centers and related assets.\n\n3. **Depreciation flows through income statement**: Once placed in service, the capitalized costs of AI infrastructure (including satellites and data center assets) depreciate and flow through the income statement as follows:\n   - **Depreciation of data center assets, including processors** → classified within **R&D expenses** (for assets used in training and development)\n   - **Depreciation of servers and networking equipment** → classified within **infrastructure costs** in **cost of revenue** (for assets used in service delivery/inference)\n\n4. **Orbital data center economics**: The company discusses how reusable launch systems and scaled satellite manufacturing will lower construction costs for orbital AI compute. The initial deployment costs of AI compute satellites are capitalized, and once deployed at scale, the company expects aggregate deployment costs to be less than terrestrial data center construction costs.\n\n### How Satellite Costs Flow Through the AI Segment\n\nThe flow can be summarized as follows:\n\n| Stage | Classification | Income Statement Line |\n|-------|---------------|----------------------|\n| Manufacturing/construction | Capitalized as Construction in Progress | Balance sheet (PP&E) |\n| Placed in service | Begin depreciation | Flows to COGS or R&D |\n| Used for training Grok | Depreciation + operating costs | R&D expenses |\n| Used for inference/service delivery | Depreciation + operating costs | Cost of revenue (infrastructure costs) |\n| Launch costs to deploy | Capitalized | Balance sheet (PP&E) |\n\n### Key Distinctions\n\n**Satellite manufacturing costs are NOT in COGS or R&D directly** — they are **capitalized** as property, plant, and equipment. The costs only reach the income statement through depreciation once the assets are placed in service, at which point the depreciation is allocated between COGS (for service delivery infrastructure) and R&D (for training infrastructure).\n\nThis treatment is consistent with the company\'s broader accounting policy where infrastructure costs — including "rocket, kit, and satellite manufacturing facilities and data center costs" — are capitalized and then depreciated, with the depreciation flowing through the appropriate income statement line based on usage.\n\n### AI Infrastructure Cost Classification Summary\n\n| Cost Type | Initial Treatment | Income Statement Classification |\n|-----------|------------------|-------------------------------|\n| Data center construction | Capitalized (PP&E) | Depreciation → COGS (infrastructure) or R&D |\n| GPU/processor procurement | Capitalized (PP&E) | Depreciation → R&D (training) or COGS (inference) |\n| Cloud computing | Expensed as incurred | R&D (training) or COGS (service delivery) |\n| AI compute satellites | Capitalized (PP&E) | Depreciation → COGS or R&D based on usage |\n| Launch costs for AI satellites | Capitalized (PP&E) | Depreciation → COGS or R&D |\n| Power/energy/bandwidth | Expensed as incurred | COGS (infrastructure costs) |\n| Employee compensation | Expensed as incurred | COGS, R&D, or SG&A based on role |\n\nThe company explicitly warns that it may choose to increase or accelerate these investments at any time, "which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
