        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Segment Reporting Policy Analysis\n\n## 1. Segment Reporting Policy\n\nBased on the disclosed notes, the company\'s segment reporting policy is as follows:\n\n**Post-Merger Realignment:** Following the Mergers, the Company evaluated how to view and measure performance of the combined company and the potential realignment of each individual entity\'s historical segment structure. Effective in **Q1 2026**, the Chief Executive Officer, acting as the **Chief Operating Decision Maker ("CODM")**, organizes the Company, manages resource allocations, and measures performance among **three operating and reportable segments**:\n\n1. **Space** — designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space\n2. **Connectivity** — operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit\n3. **AI** — operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning the frontier LLM Grok, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, and X (a real-time information platform)\n\n**Conformity of Prior Periods:** Prior period presentations for segments conform to the current segment reporting structure, meaning historical results have been recast to align with the three-segment structure.\n\n**CODM\'s Evaluation Metric:** The CODM assesses performance and allocates resources based on **segment income (loss) from operations**, by comparing actual income (loss) from operations to historical results and previously forecasted financial information. The disclosure explicitly states that the CODM **does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using** a measure other than segment income from operations (the text is truncated but the implication is that segment operating income is the sole performance measure used by the CODM for resource allocation).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Definition of Segment Income from Operations\n\nSegment income (loss) from operations is defined as **segment revenue less total segment costs and expenses**, where the significant segment expenses included are:\n\n| Line Item | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Cost of revenue | Direct costs of generating segment revenue |\n| Research and development | R&D expenditures attributable to the segment |\n| Selling, general, and administrative | SG&A costs attributable to the segment |\n| Restructuring charges | Restructuring costs attributable to the segment |\n| Impairment | Impairment charges attributable to the segment |\n\n**Items excluded from segment income from operations** (i.e., not allocated to segments and presented only at the Total Reportable Segments / consolidated level):\n\n- **Interest expense**\n- **Interest income**\n- **Other income (expense), net**\n\nThese corporate-level items are deducted after segment income from operations to arrive at **income (loss) before income taxes**.\n\n**Non-GAAP Supplemental Measure — Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** The company also defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations excluding:\n1. Depreciation and amortization\n2. Share-based compensation\n3. Restructuring charges\n4. Impairment\n\nThis is presented as a non-GAAP reconciliation but is **not** the measure used by the CODM for resource allocation (the CODM uses segment income from operations).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Costs Allocated to Segments vs. Corporate\n\n### Costs Allocated to Each Segment:\nThe following expense categories are directly attributed to each reportable segment:\n\n| Expense Category | Allocated to Segments? | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cost of revenue | ✅ Yes | Attributed directly to each segment |\n| Research and development | ✅ Yes | Attributed directly to each segment |\n| Selling, general, and administrative | ✅ Yes | Attributed directly to each segment |\n| Restructuring charges | ✅ Yes | Attributed directly to each segment (primarily AI) |\n| Impairment | ✅ Yes | Attributed directly to each segment (primarily AI) |\n\n### Costs Retained at Corporate / Consolidated Level (Not Allocated to Segments):\n| Expense Category | Allocated to Segments? | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Interest expense | ❌ No | Presented only at Total Reportable Segments level |\n| Interest income | ❌ No | Presented only at Total Reportable Segments level |\n| Other income (expense), net | ❌ No | Presented only at Total Reportable Segments level |\n| Income taxes | ❌ No | Presented only at consolidated level |\n\n### Supplemental Segment Information (Tracked by Segment but Not Part of Segment Operating Income Calculation):\nThese items are disclosed by segment as supplemental information but are **not** presented as line items within the segment costs and expenses section:\n\n- **Depreciation and amortization** — tracked by segment\n- **Share-based compensation** — tracked by segment\n- **Impairment** — tracked by segment (also appears as a line item in costs and expenses)\n- **Capital expenditures** — tracked by segment\n\n---\n\n## 4. Allocation of Depreciation, Manufacturing Costs, and Capital Expenditures to the AI Segment\n\n### Depreciation and Amortization (AI Segment)\n\nD&A is tracked at the segment level as supplemental information but is **not** a separate line item within segment costs and expenses. Instead, depreciation is embedded within the cost categories (primarily cost of revenue and potentially R&D).\n\n**AI Segment D&A:**\n| Period | AI D&A ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2023 | $1,180 |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2024 | $1,679 |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2025 | $3,568 |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2025 | $771 |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2026 | $1,493 |\n\nThe text specifically attributes the increase in AI operating losses to **"higher cloud computing and GPU depreciation costs, data center infrastructure and employee expenses."** This indicates that depreciation on GPU and data center infrastructure is a significant component of the AI segment\'s cost structure, flowing through cost of revenue (for cloud computing/GPU depreciation related to service delivery) and potentially R&D.\n\nThe dramatic increase in AI D&A (from $1,679M in 2024 to $3,568M in 2025, more than doubling) reflects the rapid buildout of compute infrastructure.\n\n### Manufacturing / Cost of Revenue (AI Segment)\n\nThe AI segment\'s cost of revenue includes the direct costs of generating AI segment revenue, which based on the narrative includes:\n- **Cloud computing costs**\n- **GPU depreciation costs**\n- **Data center infrastructure costs**\n- **Employee expenses** (partially)\n\n**AI Segment Cost of Revenue:**\n| Period | AI Cost of Revenue ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2023 | $1,655 |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2024 | $1,687 |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2025 | $2,178 |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2025 | $451 |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2026 | $456 |\n\nThe narrative states that the increase in AI loss from operations for 2025 was **"primarily driven by higher cloud computing costs, facilities-related costs and employee expenses, partially offset by higher revenue."** For Q1 2026, the $1,533 million increase in AI operating loss was **"primarily driven by higher cloud computing and GPU depreciation costs, data center infrastructure and employee expenses, partially offset by higher revenue."**\n\n### Capital Expenditures (AI Segment)\n\nCapital expenditures are tracked by segment as supplemental information. The AI segment\'s capital expenditures have scaled dramatically:\n\n**AI Segment Capital Expenditures:**\n| Period | AI CapEx ($ millions) | % of Total Segment CapEx |\n|---|---|---|\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2023 | $463 | 10.5% |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2024 | $5,633 | 50.5% |\n| Year Ended Dec 31, 2025 | $12,727 | 61.4% |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2025 | $2,567 | 62.0% |\n| Three Months Ended Mar 31, 2026 | $7,723 | 76.4% |\n\nThe company explicitly states regarding AI capital allocation:\n\n> *"We acquired xAI in February 2026, which forms the basis of our AI segment. We expect to allocate substantial capital to expand our compute infrastructure, and we expect a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA. During this investment period, our capital expenditures will scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute to address the $26.5 trillion potential market opportunity for AI."*\n\nThe company also notes that it **"plan[s] to access a range of debt and equity financing solutions available to us as a public company to fund future investments in growth and to maintain strong liquidity."**\n\nFrom the Risk Factors section, the company warns:\n\n> *"Our AI segment has incurred significant operating losses since inception, and we may not achieve profitability in this segment, or, if achieved, sustain it, and there can be no assurance that the returns on our AI investments will be adequate to justify the capital deployed."*\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe segment reporting policy establishes three reportable segments (Space, Connectivity, AI) with the CODM evaluating performance based on segment income from operations. Costs directly attributable to segments (cost of revenue, R&D, SG&A, restructuring, impairment) are allocated to segments, while financing-related items (interest expense, interest income, other income/expense) and income taxes are retained at the corporate level. For the AI segment specifically, depreciation on GPU and data center infrastructure flows through cost of revenue and R&D, driving significant operating losses. Capital expenditures for the AI segment have scaled dramatically ($12.7 billion in 2025, $7.7 billion in Q1 2026 alone), reflecting the company\'s strategy of aggressive compute infrastructure buildout with an expectation of a multi-year investment horizon before achieving sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA.',
        error=None,
