        args='{"prompt":"In {{spacex_s1}}, search for any explicit references to ASC 360, ASC 250, ASC 980, FASB, GAAP, or specific accounting standards codification references in the significant accounting policies section. Also look for the summary of significant accounting policies, particularly the property plant and equipment policy and any discussion of capitalization criteria."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, search for any explicit references to ASC 360, ASC 250, ASC 980, FASB, GAAP, or specific accounting standards codification references in the significant accounting policies section. Also look for the summary of significant accounting policies, particularly the property plant and equipment policy and any discussion of capitalization criteria.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Search Results: Accounting Standards References and PP&E Capitalization Policies\n\n## Explicit References to FASB, GAAP, and ASC Codification\n\n### FASB References\nThree explicit FASB references appear in the significant accounting policies:\n\n1. **ASU No. 2024-03** — *Disaggregation of Income Statement Expenses (Subtopic 220-40)*, issued November 2024. Requires disaggregated disclosure of specific expense categories (inventory, employee compensation, depreciation, amortization) within income statement captions, plus disclosure of total selling expenses. Effective for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2026, and interim periods within fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2027. The Company is currently evaluating its provisions.\n\n2. **ASU No. 2025-05** — *Financial Instruments—Credit Losses (Topic 326): Measurement of Credit Losses for Accounts Receivable and Contract Assets*, issued July 2025. Provides a practical expedient permitting an entity to assume balance sheet date conditions remain unchanged over the asset\'s life when estimating expected credit losses for current classified accounts receivable and contract assets. Effective for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2025.\n\n3. **ASC Topic 820, *Fair Value Measurement*** — Referenced in the fair value policy: "Financial Accounting Standards Board (\'FASB\') Accounting Standards Codification (\'ASC\') Topic 820, *Fair Value Measurement*, states that fair value is an exit price, representing the amount that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants." The three-tiered fair value hierarchy is introduced (Level I observable inputs such as quoted prices in active markets).\n\n### GAAP References\nMultiple GAAP references appear:\n\n- "The consolidated financial statements are presented in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles (\'GAAP\') in the United States of America (\'U.S.\')."\n- "The preparation of consolidated financial statements in conformity with U.S. GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities..."\n- "The preparation of financial statements and related disclosures in conformity with GAAP and the Company\'s discussion and analysis of its financial condition and operating results require the Company\'s management to make judgments, assumptions and estimates..."\n\n### ASC 360, ASC 250, ASC 980\n**No explicit references** to ASC 360 (Property, Plant, and Equipment), ASC 250 (Accounting Changes and Error Corrections), or ASC 980 (Regulated Operations) appear in the chunks provided. The property, plant, and equipment policies are described narratively without citing the specific codification topic.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (Note 2)\n\nNote 2 — *Summary of Significant Accounting Policies* is introduced multiple times across the chunks. It establishes:\n\n- **Basis of presentation**: Consolidated financial statements prepared in accordance with U.S. GAAP; intercompany balances and transactions eliminated.\n- **Unaudited interim statements**: The consolidated balance sheet as of March 31, 2026, and statements of operations, comprehensive loss, redeemable convertible preferred stock and shareholders\' equity, and cash flows for the three months ended March 31, 2026 and 2025 are unaudited. The December 31, 2025 balance sheet was derived from audited financials.\n- **Use of estimates**: Management makes estimates and assumptions affecting reported amounts. Areas subject to significant judgment include: revenues recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method, valuation allowances for deferred tax assets, tax liability estimates, reserves for excess and obsolete inventory, fair value of indefinite-lived intangible assets and goodwill, useful lives of PP&E, incremental borrowing rate for lease liabilities, litigation and settlement costs, and share-based compensation valuation. Valuation specialists are engaged for equity instrument valuations.\n\n---\n\n## Property, Plant, and Equipment Policy and Capitalization Criteria\n\n### Valuation and Depreciation\n- **Stated at cost**, less accumulated depreciation.\n- **Straight-line depreciation** over estimated useful lives, **except flight vehicles**, which are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** for each vehicle.\n- **Leasehold improvements** depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n- Management **periodically reviews useful life estimates** with engineering and operations teams and revises them as additional data becomes available.\n- When useful lives or expected remaining flights are determined to be shorter or longer than originally estimated, the **rate of depreciation is adjusted** to reflect revised useful lives or flight counts.\n\n### Estimated Useful Lives Table\n\n| Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| Servers and networking equipment | 5 – 6 years |\n| Satellites | 3 – 5 years |\n| Machinery and equipment | 3 – 10 years |\n| Flight vehicle hardware | 5 – 25 flights |\n| Data center infrastructure | 20 – 25 years |\n| Launch sites | 7 – 20 years |\n| Buildings and improvements | 30 years |\n| Leasehold improvements | Shorter of 7 – 20 years or the life of the lease |\n\n### Capitalization Criteria for Maintenance, Refurbishment, and Enhancements\n- **Maintenance and repairs** that do not extend asset lives are **expensed as incurred**.\n- **Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements** that increase functionality, output, or expected life are **capitalized and depreciated ratably** over the identified useful life.\n\n### Satellite Capitalization\n- Satellites include costs to build (parts, labor, allocated overhead) **plus capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to launch satellites to orbit, including an allocation of the flight vehicle costs.\n- **Broadband satellites**: estimated five-year useful life.\n- **First-generation mobile satellites**: estimated three-year useful life.\n- Useful life estimates based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer satellite technology.\n\n### Flight Vehicle Useful Life Estimation\nExpected flights for flight vehicle hardware are estimated based on three key criteria:\n1. Continued ability to successfully recover and refurbish hardware for additional flights.\n2. Continued economic feasibility of using hardware on incremental flights, supported by declining refurbishment costs and sensitivity analyses.\n3. Customer acceptance for reflown hardware as evidenced by the Company\'s launch manifest.\n\n### Interest Capitalization\n- The Company **capitalizes certain interest costs** associated with significant acquisition or construction of PP&E.\n- Capitalization **begins** once activities necessary to get the asset ready for its intended use have commenced.\n- **Qualified interest** is calculated using the **average accumulated expenditures** during the preparation period and a **capitalization rate** derived from the Company\'s **weighted average borrowing rate** (in the absence of specific project borrowings).\n- Capitalization **ceases** on any portions substantially completed and ready for their intended use.\n- Capitalized interest is part of the assets\' historical cost and depreciates over estimated useful lives.\n\n### Impairment Evaluation\n- The Company **evaluates impairment** of PP&E at the **lowest level** for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of other assets and liabilities.\n- Evaluation occurs **whenever events or circumstances indicate** the carrying value may not be recoverable.\n- **Indicators considered**: significant changes or planned changes in asset use, technological developments reducing utility, declines in forecasted cash flows, significant negative industry or economic trends.\n- If estimated future cash flows are less than carrying value, an **impairment charge** is recognized to the extent carrying value exceeds estimated fair value, recorded in cost of revenue or SG&A depending on asset nature, or to impairment charges if outside the normal course of business.\n\n### Capital-Related Credits\n- Capital-related credits are recorded as a **reduction to PP&E, net** and recognized as a reduction to depreciation expense over the useful life of the corresponding acquired assets, conditioned on the Company complying with agreement or statutory requirements.\n\n### Share-Based Compensation Capitalized in PP&E\n- The cash flow statement supplemental disclosures include **share-based compensation capitalized in property, plant, and equipment, net**, indicating that certain share-based compensation costs are allocated to and capitalized within PP&E.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Standards References Found\n\n| Reference | Found? | Location/Context |\n|---|---|---|\n| ASC 360 | **No** | PP&E policies described narratively without codification citation |\n| ASC 250 | **No** | Not referenced in provided chunks |\n| ASC 980 | **No** | Not referenced in provided chunks |\n| ASC 820 | **Yes** | Fair value measurement policy |\n| ASU 2024-03 (Subtopic 220-40) | **Yes** | Recent accounting pronouncements — expense disaggregation |\n| ASU 2025-05 (Topic 326) | **Yes** | Recent accounting pronouncements — credit losses practical expedient |\n| FASB | **Yes** | Three references (two ASUs, one ASC Topic 820) |\n| GAAP / U.S. GAAP | **Yes** | Multiple references in basis of presentation and use of estimates |',
