        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"In {{spacex_s1}}, what is the non-GAAP reconciliation policy for Segment Adjusted EBITDA? How is it defined and what items are excluded? Is there any discussion of why depreciation and amortization are added back? Include the exact definition and any limitations disclosed."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, what is the non-GAAP reconciliation policy for Segment Adjusted EBITDA? How is it defined and what items are excluded? Is there any discussion of why depreciation and amortization are added back? Include the exact definition and any limitations disclosed.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Non-GAAP Reconciliation Policy for Segment Adjusted EBITDA\n\n## Exact Definition\n\nBased on the disclosed text, **Segment Adjusted EBITDA is defined as segment income (loss) from operations excluding:**\n\n1. **(i) Depreciation and amortization**\n2. **(ii) Share-based compensation**\n3. **(iii) Restructuring charges**\n4. **(iv) Impairment**\n\nThis is distinct from the consolidated **Adjusted EBITDA**, which is defined as net income (loss) excluding those same four items plus (v) interest expense, (vi) interest income, (vii) other income (expense), net, and (viii) provision for income taxes. The segment-level measure begins from segment income (loss) from operations (rather than net income), so interest and tax items are already excluded at that level.\n\n## Reconciliation Approach\n\nThe company reconciles each segment\'s GAAP "Income (loss) from operations" to "Segment Adjusted EBITDA" by adding back the four excluded categories. The reconciliation tables are presented for each reportable segment (Space, Connectivity, and AI) and for Total Reportable Segments, across all reporting periods (Q1 2026, Q1 2025, FY 2025, FY 2024, and FY 2023). The company explicitly identifies segment income (loss) from operations as "the most directly comparable GAAP measure."\n\n## Discussion of Why Depreciation and Amortization Are Added Back\n\nThe disclosure does **not** provide an item-specific rationale for why depreciation and amortization are added back. Instead, it offers a general justification that applies to all excluded items:\n\n> "Management believes that certain financial measures that are not presented in accordance with GAAP provide management and investors with useful supplemental information that provides a meaningful view of our financial condition and results of operations across periods by removing the impact of items that management believes do not directly reflect our ongoing operating performance."\n\nThis statement frames D&A (along with share-based compensation, restructuring, and impairment) as items that "do not directly reflect ongoing operating performance," but no further specificity is given for D&A separately.\n\n## Stated Purpose and Use\n\nThe disclosure states that Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA "are key performance measures that our management uses to assess our financial performance as well as for internal planning and forecasting purposes." The company also considers them "meaningful performance measures for investors to evaluate our operating performance and to compare the financial results" across periods.\n\n## Limitations Disclosed\n\nThe company discloses several limitations:\n\n1. **Non-comparability across companies:** "Other companies in our industry may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all, limiting their usefulness as comparative measures."\n\n2. **Not a substitute for GAAP measures:** "Because of these limitations, Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP."\n\n3. **Must be considered alongside GAAP:** The measures "should be considered together with our GAAP financial measures and the reconciliations to the corresponding most directly comparable GAAP financial measures set forth."\n\n4. **Management acknowledges limitations:** "In evaluating our performance as measured by Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA, management recognizes and considers the limitations of these measures."\n\n## Summary\n\nThe policy is straightforward: Segment Adjusted EBITDA strips out four non-cash or non-recurring categories (D&A, share-based compensation, restructuring charges, and impairment) from segment operating income to arrive at a measure management believes better reflects ongoing operating performance. The company is careful to frame it as a supplemental—not replacement—measure, provides full reconciliations to the most directly comparable GAAP figure for every segment and period, and cautions investors about cross-company comparability and the risk of using the measure in isolation.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=17.728,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
